{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"A\n    \n      Sidebar + Settings in Main Area\n      Clicking \"Connectors\" in the activity bar shows a quick-view sidebar (status dots, toggles, tool counts). A gear icon in the sidebar header opens the full settings panel in the main content area (replacing the chat). This matches VS Code's pattern: sidebar for browsing, editor area for details.\n      \n        Pros\n          Familiar VS Code pattern\n          Sidebar stays visible while configuring\n          Full width for forms and tab content\n        \n        Cons\n          Navigating away from chat to configure\n          Two separate UI areas to maintain","choice":"a","id":null,"timestamp":1773316520743}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"B\n    \n      Sidebar Only (Expandable)\n      Everything lives in the sidebar. The default view shows the connector list. Clicking a connector expands it inline to show tools, toggle, and a \"Configure\" section. Adding a new connector opens a form within the sidebar. No separate settings panel.\n      \n        Pros\n          Single location for everything\n          Chat stays visible while managing connectors\n          Simpler navigation\n        \n        Cons\n          Sidebar width (240px) is tight for forms\n          Deep nesting: list → detail → tools → config\n          Scrolling issues with many connectors","choice":"b","id":null,"timestamp":1773316524677}
